# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: playcanvas
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] 3D computer graphics, contrary to what the name suggests, are most often displayed on two-dimensional displays.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Unlike 3D film and similar techniques, the result is two-dimensional, without visual depth.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] More often, 3D graphics are being displayed on 3D displays, like in virtual reality systems.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] 3D graphics stand in contrast to 2D computer graphics which typically use completely different methods and formats for creation and rendering.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] 3D computer graphics rely on many of the same algorithms as 2D computer vector graphics in the wire-frame model and 2D computer raster graphics in the final rendered display.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] In computer graphics software, 2D applications may use 3D techniques to achieve effects such as lighting, and similarly, 3D may use some 2D rendering techniques.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] The objects in 3D computer graphics are often referred to as 3D models.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Unlike the rendered image, a model's data is contained within a graphical data file.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] A 3D model is a mathematical representation of *any* three-dimensional object; a model is not technically a *graphic* until it is displayed.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] A model can be displayed visually as a two-dimensional image through a process called 3D rendering, or it can be used in non-graphical computer simulations and calculations.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] With 3D printing, models are rendered into an actual 3D physical representation of themselves, with some limitations as to how accurately the physical model can match the virtual model.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] William Fetter was credited with coining the term *computer graphics* in 1961 to describe his work at Boeing.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] An early example of interactive 3-D computer graphics was explored in 1963 by the Sketchpad program at Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Lincoln Laboratory.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] One of the first displays of computer animation was *Futureworld* (1976), which included an animation of a human face and a hand that had originally appeared in the 1972 experimental short *A Computer Animated Hand*, created by University of Utah students Edwin Catmull and Fred Parke.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D computer graphics software began appearing for home computers in the late 1970s.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] The earliest known example is *3D Art Graphics*, a set of 3-D computer graphics effects, written by Kazumasa Mitazawa and released in June 1978 for the Apple II.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Virtual Reality 3D is a version of 3D computer graphics.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Although the first VR headsets appeared in the late 1950s, VR did not become widely popular until the 2000s.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] In 2012 the Oculus was released and since then, the 3D VR headset world has expanded.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] The modeling describes the process of forming the shape of an object.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] The two most common sources of 3D models are those that an artist or engineer originates on a computer with a 3D modeling tool, or models scanned into a computer from real-world objects (polygonal modeling, patch modeling, and NURBS modeling are some popular tools used in 3D modeling).
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Models can also be produced procedurally or via physical simulation.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Basically, a 3D model is formed from points called vertices that define the shape and form polygons.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] A polygon is an area formed from at least three vertices (a triangle).
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] The overall integrity of the model and its suitability to use in animation depend on the structure of the polygons.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Before rendering into an image, objects must be laid out in a 3D scene.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] This defines spatial relationships between objects, including location and size.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Animation refers to the temporal description of an object (i.e., how it moves and deforms over time).
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Popular methods include keyframing, inverse kinematics, and motion-capture).
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] These techniques are often used in combination.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] As with animation, physical simulation also specifies motion.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Stop Motion has multiple categories within such as Claymation, Cutout, Silhouette, Lego, Puppets, and Pixelation.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Claymation is the use of models made of clay used for an animation.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Some examples are Clay Fighter and Clay Jam.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Lego animation is one of the more common types of stop motion.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Lego stop motion is the use of the figures themselves moving around.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Some examples of this are Lego Island and Lego Harry Potter.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Rendering converts a model into an image either by simulating light transport to get photo-realistic images, or by applying an art style as in non-photorealistic rendering.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] The two basic operations in realistic rendering are transport (how much light gets from one place to another) and scattering (how surfaces interact with light).
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] This step is usually performed using 3-D computer graphics software or a 3-D graphics API.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Altering the scene into a suitable form for rendering also involves 3D projection, which displays a three-dimensional image in two dimensions.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Materials and textures are properties that the render engine uses to render the model.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] One can give the model materials to tell the render engine how to treat light when it hits the surface.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Textures are used to give the material color using a color or albedo map, or give the surface features using a bump map or normal map.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] It can also be used to deform the model itself using a displacement map.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D computer graphics software produces computer-generated imagery (CGI) through 3D modeling and 3D rendering or produces 3-D models for analytical, scientific, entertainment, and industrial purposes.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] There are many varieties of files supporting 3-D graphics, for example, Blender (.blend), Wavefront (.obj), .fbx and .x DirectX files.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Each file type generally tends to have its own unique data structure.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Each file format can be accessed through its respective applications, such as DirectX files, and Quake.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Alternatively, files can be accessed through third-party standalone programs, or via manual decompilation.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modeling software is a class of 3-D computer graphics software used to produce 3-D models.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Individual programs of this class are called modeling applications or modelers.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modeling starts by describing 3 display models: drawing points, drawing lines and drawing triangles and other polygonal patches.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modelers allow users to create and alter models via their 3-D mesh.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Users can add, subtract, stretch and otherwise change the mesh to their desire.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Models can be viewed from a variety of angles, usually simultaneously.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Models can be rotated and the view can be zoomed in and out.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modelers can export their models to files, which can then be imported into other applications as long as the metadata are compatible.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Many modelers allow importers and exporters to be plugged-in, so they can read and write data in the native formats of other applications.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Most 3-D modelers contain a number of related features, such as ray tracers and other rendering alternatives and texture mapping facilities.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Some also contain features that support or allow animation of models.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Some may be able to generate full-motion video of a series of rendered scenes (i.e. animation).
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Computer-aided design software may employ the same fundamental 3-D modeling techniques that 3-D modeling software uses but their goal differs.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] They are used in computer-aided engineering, computer-aided manufacturing, Finite element analysis, product lifecycle management, 3D printing and computer-aided architectural design.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] After producing a video, studios then edit or composite the video using programs such as Adobe Premiere Pro or Final Cut Pro at the mid-level, or Autodesk Combustion, Digital Fusion, Shake at the high-end.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Match moving software is commonly used to match live video with computer-generated video, keeping the two in sync as the camera moves.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Use of real-time computer graphics engines to create a cinematic production is called machinima.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Not all computer graphics that appear 3D are based on a wireframe model.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics with 3D photorealistic effects are often achieved without wire-frame modeling and are sometimes indistinguishable in the final form.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Some graphic art software includes filters that can be applied to 2D vector graphics or 2D raster graphics on transparent layers.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Visual artists may also copy or visualize 3D effects and manually render photo-realistic effects without the use of filters.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Some video games use 2.5D graphics, involving restricted projections of three-dimensional environments, such as isometric graphics or virtual cameras with fixed angles, either as a way to improve performance of the game engine or for stylistic and gameplay concerns.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] By contrast, games using 3D computer graphics without such restrictions are said to use true 3D.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Cutout is the use of flat materials such as paper.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Everything is cut out of paper including the environment, characters, and even some props.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Silhouette is similar to cutouts except they are one solid color, black.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Puppets are dolls and different puppets used in the game.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] An example of this would be Yoshi's Wooly World.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] Pixelation is when the entire game appears pixelated, this includes the characters and the environment around them.
[src:playcanvas/3d-computer-graphics] One example of this is seen in Shovel Knight.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] A **game engine** is a software framework primarily designed for video game development, which may include specialized software libraries and packages, such as level editors.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] The term "engine" is a direct analogue of "software engine", having it employed across sectors of the software industry.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Furthermore, *game engine* may also refer to the integrated development environment as an interface behind the given framework, typically a suite of visual development tools and features for developing video games.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Game developers can use game engines to create and publish video games across platforms, such as desktops, mobile devices, video game consoles, and other types of computers.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] The core functionalities commonly covered by a game engine are a 2D or 3D renderer, physics engine, audio engine, scripting, animation, artificial intelligence, networking, streaming, memory management, threads, localization support, scene graph, and cinematics.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Game engine developers often economize game development through reuse or adaptation of abstractions built into game engines for production of various games, or through porting of videogames from a single to other target platforms.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] In many cases, game engines provide a suite of visual development tools in addition to reusable software components.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] These tools are generally provided in an integrated development environment to enable simplified, rapid development of games in a data-driven manner.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Game-engine developers often attempt to preempt implementer needs by developing robust software suites, which include many elements a game developer may need to build a game.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Most game-engine suites provide facilities that ease development, such as graphics, sound, physics and artificial intelligence (AI) functions.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Like other types of middleware, game engines usually provide platform abstraction, allowing the same game to run on various platforms (including game consoles and personal computers) with few, if any, changes made to the game source code.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Often, programmers design game engines with a component-based architecture that allows specific systems in the engine to be replaced or extended with more specialized (and often more expensive) game-middleware components.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Some game engines comprise a series of loosely-connected game middleware components that can be selectively combined to create a custom engine, instead of the more common approach of extending or customizing a flexible integrated product.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] However achieved, extensibility remains a high priority for game engines due to the wide variety of uses for which they are applied.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Despite the specificity of the name "game engine", end users often re-purpose game engines for other kinds of interactive applications with real-time graphical requirements—such as marketing demos, architectural visualizations, training simulations, and modeling environments.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Some game engines only provide real-time 3D rendering capabilities instead of the wide range of functionality needed by games.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] These engines rely upon the game developer to implement the rest of this functionality or to assemble it from other game-middleware components.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] These types of engines are generally referred to as a "graphics engine", "rendering engine", or "3D engine" instead of the all-encompassing term "game engine".
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] This terminology is inconsistently used, as many full-featured 3D game engines are simply referred to as "3D engines".
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Examples of graphics engines include: Crystal Space, Genesis3D, Irrlicht, OGRE, RealmForge, Truevision3D, and Vision Engine.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Modern game- or graphics-engines generally provide a scene graph—an object-oriented representation of the 3D game-world which often simplifies game design and can be used for more efficient rendering of vast virtual worlds.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Most game engines or graphics engines use a Graphics API, which eases communication with the GPU.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] But older games did not have hardware acceleration or GPUs and had to build their own software renderer.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] As technology ages, the components of an engine may become obsolete or insufficient for the requirements of a given project.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Since the complexity of programming an entirely new engine may result in unwanted delays (or necessitate that a project restart from the beginning), an engine-development team may elect to update their existing engine with newer functionality or components.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Game engines are not limited to use in the video game field, and have found uses in other scientific fields.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Part of this is due to game engines being optimized for consumer-grade computing equipment rather than high-performance computing, allowing researchers to develop programs for their use on lower cost machines.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Game engines also simplify many of the computing operations needed for scientific software, including graphics, networking, and interactivity, reducing the need to develop these features themselves.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Before game engines, games were typically written as singular entities: a game for the Atari 2600, for example, had to be designed from the bottom up to make optimal use of the display hardware—this core display routine is now called the kernel by developers of games for older systems.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Other platforms had more leeway, but even when display was not a concern, memory constraints usually sabotaged attempts to create the data-heavy design that an engine needs.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Even on more accommodating platforms, very little could be reused between games.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] The rapid advance of arcade hardware—which was the leading edge of the market at the time—meant that most of the code would have to be thrown out afterwards anyway, as later generations of games would use completely different game designs that took advantage of extra resources.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Thus, most game designs through the 1980s were designed through a hard-coded rule set with a small number of levels and graphics data.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Since the golden age of arcade video games, it became common for video game companies to develop in-house game engines for use with first-party software.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] A notable example of an in-house game engine on home consoles in the mid-1980s was the smooth side-scrolling engine developed by Shigeru Miyamoto's team at Nintendo for the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES).
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] The engine they had developed for the side-scrolling racing game *Excitebike* (1984) was later employed for the scrolling platformer *Super Mario Bros.* (1985).
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] This allowed Mario to smoothly accelerate from a walk to a run, rather than move at a constant speed like in earlier platformers.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] While third-party game engines were not common until the rise of 3D computer graphics in the 1990s, several 2D game creation systems were produced in the 1980s for independent video game development.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Klik & Play (1994) is another legacy offering that is still available.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] The term *game engine* emerged in the mid-1990s, particularly with the rise of 3D games like first-person shooters, which often featured a dedicated first-person shooter engine.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] For instance, Epic Games, founded by Tim Sweeney, debuted its Unreal Engine in 1998.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Later games, such as id Software's *Quake III Arena* and Epic Games' *Unreal* (1998), were designed with this approach in mind, with the engine and content developed separately.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] At the very least, reusable engines make developing game sequels faster and easier, which is a valuable advantage in the competitive video game industry.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] While a strong rivalry existed between Epic Games and id Software around 2000, Epic Game's Unreal Engine has since become far more popular than id Tech 4 and its successor, id Tech 5.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Modern game engines are some of the most complex applications written, often featuring dozens of finely-tuned systems interacting to ensure a precisely-controlled user experience.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] The continued evolution of game engines has created a strong separation between rendering, scripting, artwork, and level design.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] As such, it is now common, for example, for a typical game development team to have several times as many artists as actual programmers.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] While third-party game engines are predominantly used in the development of first-person shooter games, they are also being used across other genres.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] For example, Gamebryo is used in *The Elder Scrolls III: Morrowind* and *Dark Age of Camelot*, whereas Unreal Engine 2 is used in *Lineage II*.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Game engines are also used for games originally developed for home consoles, with RenderWare for the *Grand Theft Auto* and *Burnout* franchises as an example.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Due to modern multi-core systems and growing demands in realism, exploiting threads has become more important.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Separate threads of execution within a game engine manage intensive operations, including rendering, asset streaming, audio playback, and physics simulation.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Racing games have typically been at the forefront of threading with the physics engine running in a separate thread long before other core subsystems were moved, partly because rendering and related tasks need updating at only 30–60 Hz.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] For example, on PlayStation 3, physics ran in *Need For Speed* at 100 Hz, versus *Forza Motorsport 2* at 360 Hz.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Although the term was first used in the 1990s, few earlier systems in 1980s are considered as game engines, such as Sierra's Adventure Game Interpreter (AGI) and SCI systems, LucasArts' SCUMM system and Incentive Software's Freescape engine (in 1986).
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Unlike most modern game engines, these game engines were never used in any third-party products (except for the SCUMM system, which was licensed to and used by Humongous Entertainment).
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] As game engine technology matures and becomes more user friendly, the application of game engines has widened in scope.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] They are now used for serious games: visualization, training, medical, and military simulation applications, with the CryEngine being one example.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] To improve accessibility, new hardware platforms are also now targeted by game engines, including mobile phones (e.g.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Additionally, more game engines are being built upon higher-level languages, such as Java, C# and .NET (e.g., TorqueX, and Visual3D.NET), Python (Panda3D), or Lua Script (Leadwerks).
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] As most 3D-rich games are now mostly limited by the power of a graphics card, the potential slowdown due to translation overheads of higher-level languages becomes negligible, while productivity gains offered by these languages serve the game engine developers' benefit.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] These recent trends are being propelled by companies such as Microsoft to support indie game development.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Microsoft developed XNA as the primary Software Development Kit (SDK) for all video games released on Xbox and their related products.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] This includes the Xbox Live Indie Games channel designed specifically for smaller developers who do not have the extensive resources necessary to box games for sale on retail shelves.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] It is becoming easier and cheaper than ever to develop game engines for platforms that support managed frameworks.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Producers of game engines decide how they allow users to use their products.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Just as gaming is an industry, so are the engines they are built off.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] The major game engines come at varying prices, whether it be in the form of subscription fees or license payments.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Unity and Unreal Engine are currently the two most popular choices for game developers.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Although the differences among the different game engines blur as they build their own tools on top of them, different game developers may be too used to a system to change, or attracted by the huge benefits of such engines regardless of pay-walls.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Free and open-source engines such as Godot, have seen a rise in popularity, particularly following the 2023 Unity pricing controversy which drove game developers and studios to seek engines with a permissive license.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Applied more broadly, game engines themselves can be described as middleware.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] In video games, however, *middleware* is often used to refer to subsystems of functionality within a game engine.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Some game middleware does only one thing, yet does it more convincingly or more efficiently than general purpose middleware.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] The four most-widely used middleware packages that provide subsystems of functionality include RAD Game Tools' Bink, Firelight FMOD, Havok, and Scaleform GFx.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] RAD Game Tools develops Bink for basic video rendering, along with Miles audio, and Granny 3D rendering.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Firelight FMOD is a low cost robust audio library and toolset.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Havok provides a robust physics simulation system, along with a suite of animation and behavior applications.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Scaleform provides GFx for high performance Flash UI and high-quality video playback, and an Input Method Editor (IME) addon for in-game Asian chat support.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Other middleware is used for performance optimization—for example Simplygon helps to optimize and generate level of detail meshes, and Umbra adds occlusion culling optimizations to 3D graphics.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Some middleware contains full source code, or is provided an API reference for a compiled binary library.
[src:playcanvas/game-engine] Some middleware programs can be licensed either way, usually for a higher fee for full source code.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:playcanvas/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:playcanvas/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:playcanvas/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:playcanvas/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
