[src:playcanvas/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:playcanvas/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:playcanvas/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:playcanvas/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:playcanvas/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:playcanvas/playcanvas] PlayCanvas has gained the support of ARM, Activision and Mozilla.
[src:playcanvas/playcanvas] The PlayCanvas engine was open-sourced on June 4, 2014.
[src:playcanvas/playcanvas] In April 2019, BusinessInsider.com reported that the company was acquired by Snap Inc. in 2017.
[src:playcanvas/playcanvas] The PlayCanvas platform has collaborative real-time Editor that allows editing a project by multiple developers simultaneously.
[src:playcanvas/playcanvas] The engine supports the WebGL 1.0 and 2.0 standard to produce GPU accelerated 3D graphics and allows for scripting via the JavaScript programming language.
[src:playcanvas/playcanvas] Projects can be distributed via a URL web link or packaged in native wrappers, p.g. for Android, using CocoonJS or for Steam using Electron, and many other options and platforms.
[src:playcanvas/playcanvas] Various companies use PlayCanvas in projects of different disciplines of interactive 3D content in the web.
[src:playcanvas/playcanvas] Disney created an educational game for Hour of Code based on its *Moana* film.
[src:playcanvas/playcanvas] King published *Shuffle Cats Mini,* as a launch title for Facebook Instant Games.
[src:playcanvas/playcanvas] TANX – massively multiplayer online game of cartoon styled tanks.
[src:playcanvas/playcanvas] Miniclip published number of games on their platform with increase of HTML5 games popularity on the web.
[src:playcanvas/playcanvas] Mozilla collaborated with PlayCanvas team creating *After the Flood* demo for presenting cutting-edge features of WebGL 2.0.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] WebGL programs consist of control code written in JavaScript, and shader code written in OpenGL ES Shading Language (GLSL ES, sometimes referred to as ESSL), a language similar to C or C++.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] WebGL code is executed on a computer's GPU.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] WebGL is designed and maintained by the non-profit Khronos Group.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] On February 9, 2022, Khronos Group announced WebGL 2.0 support from all major browsers.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] From 2024, a new graphics API, WebGPU, is being developed to supersede WebGL.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] WebGPU provides extended capabilities, a more modern interface, and direct GPU access, which is useful for demanding graphics as well as AI applications.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] WebGL 1.0 is based on OpenGL ES 2.0 and provides an API for 3D graphics.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] It uses the HTML5 canvas element and is accessed using Document Object Model (DOM) interfaces.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] It guarantees the availability of many optional extensions of WebGL 1.0, and exposes new APIs.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] Automatic memory management is provided implicitly by JavaScript.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] Like OpenGL ES 2.0, WebGL lacks the fixed-function APIs introduced in OpenGL 1.0 and deprecated in OpenGL 3.0.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] This functionality, if required, has to be implemented by the developer using shader code and JavaScript.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] Shaders in WebGL are written in GLSL and passed to the WebGL API as text strings.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] The WebGL implementation compiles these strings to GPU code.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] This code is executed for each vertex sent through the API and for each pixel rasterized to the screen.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] WebGL evolved out of the Canvas 3D experiments started by Vladimir Vukićević at Mozilla.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] Vukićević first demonstrated a Canvas 3D prototype in 2006.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] By the end of 2007, both Mozilla and Opera had made their own separate implementations.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] In early 2009, the non-profit technology consortium Khronos Group started the WebGL Working Group, with initial participation from Apple, Google, Mozilla, Opera, and others.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] Version 1.0 of the WebGL specification was released March 2011.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] An early application of WebGL was Zygote Body.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] In November 2012 Autodesk announced that they ported most of their applications to the cloud running on local WebGL clients.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] These applications included Autodesk Fusion and AutoCAD.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] Development of the WebGL 2 specification started in 2013 and finished in January 2017.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] The specification is based on OpenGL ES 3.0.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] First implementations are in Firefox 51, Chrome 56 and Opera 43.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] Almost Native Graphics Layer Engine (ANGLE) is an open source graphic engine which implements WebGL 1.0 (2.0 which closely conforms to ES 3.0) and OpenGL ES 2.0 and 3.0 standards.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] It is a default backend for both Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox on Windows platforms and works by translating WebGL and OpenGL calls to available platform-specific APIs.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] WebGL is widely supported by modern browsers.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] However, its availability depends on other factors, too, like whether the GPU supports it.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] The official WebGL website offers a simple test page.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] More detailed information (like what renderer the browser uses, and what extensions are available) can be found at third-party websites.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] Some such libraries were ported to JavaScript from other languages.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] Examples of libraries that provide high-level features include A-Frame (VR), BabylonJS, PlayCanvas, three.js, OSG.JS, Google’s model-viewer and CopperLicht.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] Web3D also made a project called X3DOM to make X3D and VRML content run on WebGL.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] There has been an emergence of 2D and 3D game engines for WebGL, such as Unreal Engine 4 and Unity.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] The Stage3D/Flash-based Away3D high-level library also has a port to WebGL via TypeScript.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] A more light-weight utility library that provides just the vector and matrix math utilities for shaders is sylvester.js.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] It is sometimes used in conjunction with a WebGL specific extension called glUtils.js.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] There are also some 2D libraries built atop WebGL, like Cocos2d-x or Pixi.js, which were implemented this way for performance reasons in a move that parallels what happened with the Starling Framework over Stage3D in the Flash world.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] The WebGL-based 2D libraries fall back to HTML5 canvas when WebGL is not available.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] Removing the rendering bottleneck by giving almost direct access to the GPU has exposed performance limitations in the JavaScript implementations.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] Some were addressed by asm.js and WebAssembly (similarly, the introduction of Stage3D exposed performance problems within ActionScript, which were addressed by projects like CrossBridge).
[src:playcanvas/webgl] As with any other graphics API, creating content for WebGL scenes requires using a 3D content creation tool and exporting the scene to a format that is readable by the viewer or helper library.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] Desktop 3D authoring software such as Blender, Autodesk Maya or SimLab Composer can be used for this purpose.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] In particular, Blend4Web allows a WebGL scene to be authored entirely in Blender and exported to a browser with a single click, even as a standalone web page.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] There are also some WebGL-specific software such as CopperCube and the online WebGL-based editor Clara.io.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] Online platforms such as Sketchfab and Clara.io allow users to directly upload their 3D models and display them using a hosted WebGL viewer.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] Starting from Firefox Version 27, Mozilla has given Firefox built-in WebGL tools that allow the editing of vertices and fragment shaders.
[src:playcanvas/webgl] A number of other debugging and profiling tools have also emerged.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] In JavaScript, WebGPU can be provided by a web browser or other JavaScript environment like Node.js and Deno.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] Rust and C++ can use their respective implementations of the WebGPU specification.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] Other languages like Python, Java, and Go can use WebGPU by extending the C language specification.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] Google Chrome and Microsoft Edge first released WebGPU support in April 2023.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] Safari debuted WebGPU support in June 2025 with Safari 26.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] Firefox first released WebGPU in July 2025 with Firefox 141.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] The W3C standard is a candidate recommendation.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] WebGPU enables 3D graphics within an HTML canvas.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] It also has robust support for general-purpose GPU computations.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] WebGPU uses its own shading language called WebGPU Shading Language (WGSL) that was designed to be trivially translatable to SPIR-V, until complaints caused redirection into a more traditional design, similar to other shading languages.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] Tint is a Google-made compiler for WGSL.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] Naga is a similar project developed for the needs of wgpu-rs.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] Both Google Chrome and Firefox support WebGPU and WGSL.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] Firefox and Deno use the Rust wgpu library.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] Safari follows upstream specifications of both WebGPU and WGSL.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] Chrome version 113 enabled initial WebGPU support on Windows devices with Direct3D 12, ChromeOS devices with Vulkan, and macOS with Metal.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] This support for Android was enabled in version 121.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] On June 8, 2016, Google showed "Explicit web graphics API" presentation to the WebGL working group (during the bi-annual face to face meeting).
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] The presentation explored the basic ideas and principles of building a new API to eventually replace WebGL, aka "WebGL Next".
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] On January 24, 2017, Khronos hosted an IP-free meeting dedicated to discussion of "WebGL Next" ideas, collided with WebGL working group meeting in Vancouver.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] Google team presented the NXT prototype implementing a new API that could run in Chromium with OpenGL, or standalone with OpenGL and Metal.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] NXT borrowed concepts from all of Vulkan, Direct3D 12, and Metal native APIs.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] Apple and Mozilla representatives also showed their prototypes built on Safari and Servo correspondingly, both of which closely replicated the Metal API.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] On February 7, 2017, Apple's WebKit team proposed the creation of the W3C community group to design the API.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] At the same time they announced a technical proof of concept and proposal under the name "WebGPU", based on concepts in Apple's Metal.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] The WebGPU name was later adopted by the community group as a working name for the future standard rather than just Apple's initial proposal.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] The initial proposal has been renamed to "WebMetal" to avoid further confusion.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] The W3C "GPU for the Web" Community Group was launched on February 16, 2017.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] At this time, all of Apple, Google, and Mozilla had experiments in the area, but only Apple's proposal was officially submitted to the "gpuweb-proposals" repository.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] Shortly after, on March 21, 2017, Mozilla submitted a proposal for WebGL Next within Khronos repository, based on the Vulkan design.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] On June 1, 2018, citing "resolution on most-high level issues" in the cross-browser standardization effort, Google's Chrome team announced intent to implement the future WebGPU standard.
[src:playcanvas/webgpu] On 13 February, 2020, Google unveiled Tint as an alternative to WHLSL textual language proposal to WebGPU API, and the language eventually became the standardized WebGPU Shading Language (WGSL), and Tint became the name of compiler within Dawn, the WebGPU implementation of Chromium.
